<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="454" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="53" pageNumber="454">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,367,392]" pageId="53" pageNumber="454">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific name is from the Latin for “velvety”, referring to the velvety brown aspect of the epicephalon and vertex of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="454" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="53" pageNumber="454">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,439,464]" pageId="53" pageNumber="454">Comments:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[344,634,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="velutinosa">
<emphasis box="[344,634,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="454">Cardiacephala velutinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other 
<taxonomicName box="[844,1011,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[844,1011,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="454">Cardiacephala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its velvety brown epicephalon and vertex. The small ejaculatory apodeme is also a remarkable character. Genitalia of the unique female specimen were not examined.
</paragraph>
